Japanese Stocks in U.S., Australia Shares Retreat on U.S. Retail Data, Oil

-- B y   A k i k o   I k e d a   a n d   K o t a r o   T s u n e t o m i
-- 
2011-02-15T23:18:23Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-15/japanese-stocks-in-u-s-australia-shares-retreat-on-u-s-retail-data-oil.html
Japanese stocks traded in the U.S.
and Australian shares fell after commodity prices declined
and reports showed retail sales in the U.S. increased less
than expected in January.  The Bank of New York Mellon Japan ADR Index slid 0.3
percent yesterday. American depositary receipts of Nissan
Motor Co., a Japanese carmaker which counts  North America  as
its biggest market, slipped 0.2 percent from the closing
share price in Tokyo. Those of Sumitomo Mitsui Financial
Group Inc., Japan’s second-largest publicly traded bank, lost
0.4 percent after Tokai Tokyo Securities cut its rating on
the company. BHP Billiton Ltd.,  Australia ’s biggest oil and
gas producer, retreated 1.1 percent in Sydney today.  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225  Stock Average expiring in
March closed at 10,750 in  Chicago  yesterday, compared with
10,740 in Osaka. They were bid in the pre-market at 10,750 in
Osaka, Japan, at 8:05 a.m. local time. Australia’s S&P/ASX
200 Index fell 0.2 percent today.  New Zealand ’s NZX 50 Index
slid 0.3 percent in Wellington.  “Gains in commodity-related stocks will likely come to
a halt,” following a drop in  oil prices , said  Hiroichi Nishi ,
an equities manager in Tokyo at Nikko Cordial Securities Inc.
“The market looks overheated after the Topix advanced for a
seventh day yesterday.”  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index were little
changed today. In New York, the index retreated 0.3 percent
to 1,328.01 yesterday after a report showed retail sales
increased less than forecast and Exxon Mobil Corp. led a
decline in energy producers.  U.S. Retail Sales  Commerce Department figures showed that retail purchases
increased 0.3 percent in January, the smallest gain since a
drop in June. The median forecast of economists surveyed by
Bloomberg News called for a 0.5 percent rise. Other reports
showed manufacturing in the  New York  area accelerated and
confidence among home builders stagnated.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index slid less than 0.1 percent
through yesterday in 2011, compared with gains of 5.6 percent
by the S&P 500 and 4.9 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index.
Stocks in the Asian benchmark are valued at 14.1 times
estimated earnings on average, compared with 13.8 times for
the  S&P 500  and 11.4 times for the Stoxx 600.  Crude oil for March delivery slipped 0.6 percent to
settle at $84.32 a barrel in New York yesterday, the lowest
level since Nov. 30. The London Metal Exchange Index of
prices for six industrial metals including copper and
aluminum dropped 1 percent yesterday. Copper futures for May
delivery fell 0.9 percent.  The yen depreciated to as low as 83.84 against the
dollar today, compared with 83.46 at the close of  stock
trading  in Tokyo. Against the euro, Japan’s currency weakened
to 113.36 from 112.87. A weaker yen boosts the value of
overseas income at Japanese companies when converted into
their home currency.  To contact the reporters on this story:
